ut 1125","Broyes, Marne, Grand Est, France":"Broyes, Marne, Grand Est, France","Broyes, Marne, France":"Broyes, Marne, Grand Est, France","France":"France","Baye, Marne, Grand Est, France":"Baye, Marne, Grand Est, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Broyes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Breyhel</b>, a variant of <b>Breil</b>, itself a variant of <b>Brühl</b> (see   Bruehl  ). The surname <i>Breyhel</i> is no longer found in Germany. Compare   Briles  .","History: Johannes Breyhel and his family, from Oetisheim in Württemberg, were among a group of German colonists sponsored by VA Governor Alexander Spotswood in 1714. They founded a settlement called Germanna in Orange County. Hans Jacob Breyhel (born 1705) was the ancestor of the Broyles family, while his brother Conrad was founder of the Briles family."],"variants":[{"name":"Bruehl","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Armin, Dieter, Frieda, Horst, Lothar.","German (<b>Brühl</b>): topographic name for someone who lived by a swampy area, Middle High German <i>brüel</i>, Middle Low German <i>brūl</i> ‘swampy land with brushwood’.","German and Jewish (western Ashkenazic) (<b>Brühl</b>): habitational name from Brühl in Germany. Compare   Bruhl  ."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Simon Seigneur de Broyes I was born about 1095, in Broyes, Marne, Grand Est, France, his father, Hugues II de Broyes, was 34 and his mother, Emmeline de Montlhéry, was 22. He married Felicity Brienne about 1125. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died on 4 January 1140, in Baye, Marne, Grand Est, France, at the age of 46."},"et":{"Abt 1095–4 January 1140":"umbes 1095–4. jaanuar 1140","1095–1140":"1095–1140","1104–1178":"1104–1178","1120–1199":"1120–1199","1124–1136":"1124–1136","1136–1188":"1136–1188","1062–1112":"1062–1112","1075–1121":"1075–1121","1121":"1121","1120":"1120","1075":"1075","1140":"1140","1062":"1062","1095":"1095","4 January 1140":"4. jaanuar 1140","Abt 1095":"umbes 1095","1104":"1104","1136":"1136","1124":"1124","1112":"1112","1178":"1178","1188":"1188","1199":"1199","about 1125":"umbes 1125","Broyes, Marne, Grand Est, France":"Broyes, Marne, Grand Est, Prantsusmaa","Broyes, Marne, France":"Broyes, Marne, Grand Est, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa","Baye, Marne, Grand Est, France":"Baye, Marne, Grand Est, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1095–4 January 1140":"noin 1095–4. tammikuut